This restaurant is a jewel in the neighborhood. I ordered L1, the lunch special of 6 pieces of chicken teriyaki and 6 California Roll,(I am not adventurous when it comes to sushi). The dish looked small, however, it was compact. In fact, it was enough for two servings, half I ate there, and the remainder I took home to eat the next day.  The salad was crisp and fresh. The white rice absorbed the teriyaki sauce, which was more liquefied than thick, so I requested another container to pour onto the meat, cooked to perfection. If you do not have cash, a $10 minimum order is required to use a credit/debit card. Therefore, I had the gyoza, the dumpling like dish with a meatball-like center of pork, and a soft drink. Total: 12 bucks. Affordable and worth it. The dish is a good representation of the photo on the menu, so you do get what you pay for. I ate in the restaurant around 2 p.m. and had it to myself as the lone customer for about 15 minutes. The meal was tasty, hearty, and did my soul good. I shall return. Word of caution,, I read the reviews prior to going, which rated well for dining in, but ranked low for the delivery service; not the food.

We were served by the same waiter about two weeks ago. It was a large order, it cost around $68. The food was great however coming back to make another order today about a hour ago, I was asked for ID for our order which cost about $34.  Asking the reason for the ID since only one person made the order and it was more than now, an immense amount of attitude was given.  The Asian lady at the counter started acting belligerent and asking “what you mean”! One of the guys was sitting at the table actually right away he wanted to leave. We ended up canceling the order. I don’t care how good the food is there is no excuse to act the way she was acting. In today’s world we do not know if being ID is either a racial response, or  If someone just placed in a new procedure  since there is no signage indicating an ID is need for verification. On another note it was a business credit card that was being used so a personal ID wouldn’t be sufficient in those transactions.  Learn how to respect people is the biggest Takeaway this person can have  she was spoken to in a complete respectful tone to whereas the entire group was confused actually looked at her . We will never be there again. Keep in mind many of us grew up in this area and was here Way before sushi was no where outside of 86st, 18th age and ave u.  If any transaction is on the card since it was swiped, it will be disputed.  In our business we will be destroyed if we had the etiquette , or in this case lack of etiquette is this lady had which should be a basic characteristic  especially any field that is customer facing
